{"cursor":"51152","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Monism' is a philosophical position which argues that the variety of existing\nthings can be explained in terms of a single reality. It is sometimes used\nsimply to mean that all existing things go back to a source which is distinct\nfrom them, but it is commonly understood to imply not only unity of origin but\nalso of substance and essence. Therefore, the fundamental character of the\nuniverse is unity.\n\nContrasting with this point of view are metaphysical dualism, which asserts that\nthere are two ultimately irreconcilable substances or realities such as Good and\nEvil, for example, Manichaeism, and metaphysical pluralism, which asserts three\nor more fundamental substances or realities.\n","linknr":1737,"url":"Monism","recorded":1362477058,"links":81,"instances":["buddhism","spiritual","priest","philosophy","philosophy_of_mind","psychology","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy_of_mind","book","archangel","theology","illusion","philosophy","philosophy","theology","religion","theologian"],"pdf":["http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/HistoricalZen/translating_zen_phrasebook.pdf","http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/HistoricalZen/translating_zen_phrasebook.pdf","http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.122.8740&rep=rep1&type=pdf","http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.122.8740&rep=rep1&type=pdf","http://buddhiststudies.berkeley.edu/people/faculty/sharf/documents/Sharf1995,%20Buddhist%20Modernism.pdf","http://buddhiststudies.berkeley.edu/people/faculty/sharf/documents/Sharf1995,%20Buddhist%20Modernism.pdf"],"categories":["Monism|","Theology","Metaphysical theories","Theories of mind","Reductionism"],"headings":["History and definition","Types of monism","Philosophical monism","Religious monism","See also","Notes","References","Sources","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/28/P_religion_world.svg/31px-P_religion_world.svg.p